\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 ## 1. Project Overview
\f1\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb3 \strokec4 Mining Law AI is a Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) chatbot that answers questions about Indian mining law. It retrieves relevant passages from a curated set of legal PDFs and uses a large language model to generate concise, cited answers.\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\cb3 \strokec4 The system is designed to be deployable on Streamlit Community Cloud with zero infrastructure cost, using Groq's free API tier for LLM inference.\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\cb3 \strokec4 ---\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 ## 2. Architecture
\f1\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 ### 2.1 High-Level Flow
\f1\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb3 \strokec4 ```\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 User Question\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4      \uc0\u8595 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 Embed question (all-MiniLM-L6-v2)\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4      \uc0\u8595 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 FAISS MMR Search \uc0\u8594  Top 4 relevant chunks\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4      \uc0\u8595 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 Build prompt with context + question\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4      \uc0\u8595 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 Groq API (Mixtral-8x7B) \uc0\u8594  Generate answer\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4      \uc0\u8595 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 Extract citations (source, page, section)\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4      \uc0\u8595 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 Display answer + citations in Streamlit UI\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4      \uc0\u8595 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 Save to chat_history.json\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 ```\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 ### 2.2 Component Breakdown
\f1\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb3 \strokec4 | Component | Technology | Purpose |\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 |---|---|---|\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 | PDF Loading | PDFPlumber | Extracts text from legal PDFs with better layout handling than pypdf |\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 | Text Splitting | RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter | Splits on paragraphs \uc0\u8594  sentences \u8594  words to avoid mid-sentence cuts |\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 | Embeddings | all-MiniLM-L6-v2 | Converts text to 384-dimensional vectors for similarity search |\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 | Vector Store | FAISS | Facebook AI Similarity Search \'97 fast local index, no external DB needed |\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 | Retrieval | MMR (Maximal Marginal Relevance) | Retrieves relevant AND diverse chunks \'97 prevents 4 identical results |\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 | LLM (cloud) | Groq \'97 Mixtral-8x7B | Cloud inference, fast, free tier, instruction-tuned |\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 | LLM (local) | Ollama \'97 Mistral 7B | Local inference for development on Apple Silicon |\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 | Frontend | Streamlit | Python-native web framework, deployable with one click |\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 | History | JSON file | Persistent chat sessions, portable across deployments |\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\cb3 \strokec4 ---\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 ## 3. Configuration Parameters
\f1\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb3 \strokec4 All parameters are defined at the top of \cf2 \strokec2 `app_ui.py`\cf0 \strokec4  for easy tuning:\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\cb3 \strokec4 | Parameter | Current Value | Effect |\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 |---|---|---|\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 | \cf2 \strokec2 `CHUNK_SIZE`\cf0 \strokec4  | 700 chars | Size of each text chunk. Too small = loses context. Too large = noisy retrieval. |\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 | \cf2 \strokec2 `CHUNK_OVERLAP`\cf0 \strokec4  | 100 chars | Overlap between chunks. Prevents answers cut off at boundaries. |\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 | \cf2 \strokec2 `TOP_K`\cf0 \strokec4  | 4 | Number of chunks retrieved per query. More = richer context, more noise. |\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 | \cf2 \strokec2 `GROQ_MODEL`\cf0 \strokec4  | mixtral-8x7b-32768 | LLM model used for answer generation. |\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 | \cf2 \strokec2 `EMBEDDING_MODEL`\cf0 \strokec4  | all-MiniLM-L6-v2 | Embedding model. Faster alternatives exist but lower accuracy. |\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\cb3 \strokec4 ---\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 ## 4. Key Design Decisions
\f1\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 ### 4.1 Why FAISS over ChromaDB or Pinecone?
\f1\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb3 \strokec4 FAISS runs entirely locally with no external service, no API calls, and no cost. The index is saved as a folder and can be committed to a repo or bundled with deployment. For a document set under 1000 pages, FAISS performance is more than sufficient.\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 ### 4.2 Why MMR retrieval over plain similarity search?
\f1\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb3 \strokec4 Plain similarity search can return 4 chunks from the same paragraph if the query matches that paragraph strongly. MMR balances relevance with diversity \'97 each retrieved chunk must be relevant but also different from already-selected chunks. This gives the LLM broader context.\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 ### 4.3 Why Groq over OpenAI?
\f1\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb3 \strokec4 Groq offers a free tier with generous rate limits. Mixtral-8x7B on Groq is faster than GPT-3.5 and comparable in quality for legal Q&A. No credit card required for the free tier.\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 ### 4.4 Why RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter?
\f1\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb3 \strokec4 Legal documents have deeply nested structure: parts \uc0\u8594  chapters \u8594  sections \u8594  sub-sections \u8594  clauses. RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter attempts splits in order: paragraph breaks \u8594  line breaks \u8594  sentence ends \u8594  word boundaries. This preserves legal sentence structure far better than simple character splitting.\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 ### 4.5 Why PDFPlumber over PyPDF?
\f1\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb3 \strokec4 Legal PDFs from Indian government sources often have complex column layouts, headers, and footers. PDFPlumber handles these better and extracts cleaner text with more accurate page metadata.\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\cb3 \strokec4 ---\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 ## 5. Prompt Engineering
\f1\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb3 \strokec4 The LLM prompt uses Mistral/Mixtral's native \cf2 \strokec2 `[INST]...[/INST]`\cf0 \strokec4  instruction format:\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\cb3 \strokec4 ```\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 [INST] You are a legal assistant specializing in Indian mining law.\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\cb3 \strokec4 Use ONLY the context provided below to answer the question.\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 - Answer in 2-3 clear, complete sentences.\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 - If a specific Section or Rule number appears in the context, mention it.\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 - Do not copy text verbatim.\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 - If not found, say: "This information was not found in the provided documents."\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 - Never invent section numbers or rules.\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\cb3 \strokec4 Context: \{retrieved chunks\}\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 Question: \{user question\} [/INST]\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 ```\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\cb3 \strokec4 Key constraints enforced in the prompt:\cb1 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \cb3 \strokec6 -\cf0 \strokec4  Answer length capped at 2\'963 sentences (prevents rambling)\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cf6 \cb3 \strokec6 -\cf0 \strokec4  Section number citation required when present (improves answer quality)\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cf6 \cb3 \strokec6 -\cf0 \strokec4  Hallucination prevention ("never invent" instruction)\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cf6 \cb3 \strokec6 -\cf0 \strokec4  Graceful fallback when answer not found\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb3 \strokec4 ---\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 ## 6. Citation Extraction
\f1\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb3 \strokec4 After retrieval, each chunk is scanned with a regex to extract legal references:\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\cb3 \strokec4 ```python\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 re.search(\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4     \cf7 \strokec7 r\cf8 \strokec8 '\\b(Section\cf0 \strokec4 |\cf8 \strokec8 Sec\\.\cf0 \strokec4 |\cf8 \strokec8 Rule\cf0 \strokec4 |\cf8 \strokec8 Regulation\cf0 \strokec4 |\cf8 \strokec8 Clause\cf0 \strokec4 |\cf8 \strokec8 Article\cf0 \strokec4 |\cf8 \strokec8 Schedule)\\s\cf0 \strokec4 +\cf8 \strokec8 (\\d\cf0 \strokec4 +\cf8 \strokec8 [\\w\\(\\)\\.]\cf0 \strokec4 *\cf8 \strokec8 )'\cf0 \strokec4 ,\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4     text, re.IGNORECASE\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 )\cb1 \strokec4 \
\cb3 \strokec4 ```\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\cb3 \strokec4 This captures references like:\cb1 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \cb3 \strokec6 -\cf0 \strokec4  \cf2 \strokec2 `Section 5`\cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\cf6 \cb3 \strokec6 -\cf0 \strokec4  \cf2 \strokec2 `Rule 22(1)`\cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\cf6 \cb3 \strokec6 -\cf0 \strokec4  \cf2 \strokec2 `Regulation 4`\cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\cf6 \cb3 \strokec6 -\cf0 \strokec4  \cf2 \strokec2 `Schedule II`\cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\cf6 \cb3 \strokec6 -\cf0 \strokec4  \cf2 \strokec2 `Clause 3(a)`\cf0 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb3 \strokec4 Citations are stored with each message in \cf2 \strokec2 `chat_history.json`\cf0 \strokec4  so they persist when revisiting old chats.\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\cb3 \strokec4 ---\cb1 \strokec4 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

